            <p>One way to establish this formula is to imagine slicing up the circle into many pie slices as in <xref ref="figure-circle-area">Figure</xref>. Then you can rearrange the slices into a strange shape that is <em>almost</em> a rectangle with height equal to the radius of the original circle, and width equal to half the circumference of the original circle.</p>

            <figure xml:id="figure-circle-area">
                <caption>Reasoning the circle area formula.</caption>
                    <image width="100%">
                    <description></description>
                    <latex-image>
                       <![CDATA[
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[x=1.8cm,y=1.8cm]
                                %grid
                                \draw[step=1,very thin, opacity=0.5] (-1,-1) grid (7,3);
